      • onInstalling

        public abstract void onInstalling()
        When a new service worker is registered using navigator.serviceWorker.register, the JavaScript is downloaded, parsed, and enters the installing _state. If the installation succeeds, the service worker will proceed to the installed _state. If however, an error occurs during installation, the script will instead be banished to the abyss of the redundant _state for all eternity (or until you attempt to register it again by refreshing the page).

      • onInstalled

        public abstract void onInstalled()
        Once a service worker has successfully installed, it enters the installed _state. It will then immediately move on to the activating _state unless another active service worker is currently controlling this app, in which case it will remain waiting.

      • onActivating

        public abstract void onActivating()
        Before a service worker becomes active and takes control of your app, the activate event is triggered. Similar to the installing _state, the activating _state can also be extended by calling event.waitUntil() and passing it a promise.

      • onActivated

        public abstract void onActivated()
        Once a service worker is activated, it is ready to take control of the page and listen to functional events (such as fetch). A service worker can only take control of pages before they start loading. This means that pages that began loading before the service worker became active cannot be controlled by it.

      • onRedundant

        public abstract void onRedundant()
        Service workers that failed during registration, or installation, or were replaced by newer versions, are placed in the redundant _state. Service workers in this _state no longer have any effect on your app.

      • onControllerChange

        protected abstract void onControllerChange()
        Will listen to any event fired by the service worker.

      • onNewServiceWorkerFound

        Called when there are new service worker updates on the appcache.
